# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: picture-in-picture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] MVC formatting is intended for encoding stereoscopic (two-view) 3D video, as well as free viewpoint television and multi-view 3D television.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] The Stereo High profile has been standardized in June 2009; the profile is based on the MVC tool set and is used in stereoscopic Blu-ray 3D releases.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] MVC is based on the idea that video recordings of the same scene from multiple angles share many common elements.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] It is possible to encode all simultaneous frames captured in the same elementary stream and to share as much information as possible across the different layers.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] This can reduce the size of the encoded video.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] Multiview video contains a large amount of inter-view statistical dependencies, since all cameras capture the same scene from different viewpoints.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] Therefore, combined temporal and inter-view prediction is important for efficient MVC encoding.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] A frame from a certain camera can be predicted not only from temporally related frames from the same camera, but also from the frames of neighboring cameras.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] These interdependencies can be used for efficient prediction.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] The method for this used in Multiview Video Coding for Blu-ray 3D movies is known as the 2D plus Delta algorithm, and the MVC specification itself is part of the H.264 standard as an amendment in H.264 “Annex H” of the specification.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] As of April 2015, there is no free and open-source software that supports software decoding of the MVC video compression standard.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] Popular open source H.264 and HEVC (H.265) decoders, such as those used in the FFmpeg and Libav libraries, simply ignore the second view and thus do not show the second view for stereoscopic views.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] In most cases, the reason for this support not being added is that MVC was not considered when the initial core H.264 and HEVC decoders code was written.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] Some proof-of-concept work has however been done downstream in the past, but never made it upstream into official releases of FFmpeg or Libav.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] On March 8, 2016, the situation improved.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] Version 0.68 of the DirectShow Media Splitter and Decoders Collection LAV Filters was released by developer "Nevcairiel" (who also works for Media Player Classic — Home Cinema (MPC-HC)) with support of H.264 MVC 3D demuxing and decoding.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] With the aid of this release and FRIM written by a programmer named “videohelp3d” it is possible to write an AviSynth script to pre process a H.264 MVC 3D video clip which can then be opened by free 3D video player Bino and then shown as red — cyan anaglyph video for example.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] The usage of the FRIM AviSynth plugin (FRIMSource) is described on “videohelp3d” home page.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] LAV Filters can be used to get audio from H.264 MVC 3D video clip.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] The developer posted that in a future release of, it might be possible that LAV Video renders the video as Side-by-Side directly.
[src:picture-in-picture/multiview-video-coding] The following organizations hold patents that contributed to the development of MVC technology, listed in a patent pool by MPEG LA.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The **Picture-in-Picture API** allow websites to create a floating, always-on-top video window.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] This allows users to continue consuming media while they interact with other sites or applications on their device.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] To run code in response to such actions, set up a media session action handler using `MediaSession.setActionHandler()` with a `type` of `enterpictureinpicture`.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] Represents the floating video window; contains `width` and `height` properties, and an `onresize` event handler property.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] Represents picture-in-picture-related events, including `enterpictureinpicture`, `leavepictureinpicture` and `resize`.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The Picture-in-Picture API adds methods to the `HTMLVideoElement` and `Document` interfaces to allow toggling of the floating video window.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] Requests that the user agent returns the element in picture-in-picture mode back into its original box.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The Picture-in-Picture API augments the `HTMLVideoElement`, `Document`, and `ShadowRoot` interfaces with properties that can be used to determine if the floating video window mode is supported and available, if picture-in-picture mode is currently active, and which video is floating.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The `disablePictureInPicture` property will provide a hint to the user agent to not suggest the picture-in-picture to users or to request it automatically.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The `pictureInPictureEnabled` property tells you whether or not it is possible to engage picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] This is `false` if picture-in-picture mode is not available for any reason (e.g., the `"picture-in-picture"` feature has been disallowed, or picture-in-picture mode is not supported).
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The `pictureInPictureElement` property tells you which `Element` is currently being displayed in the floating window (or in the shadow DOM).
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] If this is `null`, the document (or shadow DOM) has no node currently in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] Sent to a `HTMLVideoElement` when it enters picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] Sent to a `HTMLVideoElement` when it leaves picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] Sent to a `PictureInPictureWindow` when it changes size.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] If media action handlers have been set via the Media Session API, then appropriate controls for those actions will be added by the browser to the picture-in-picture overlay.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] For example, if a `"nexttrack"` action has been set, then a skip button might be displayed in the picture-in-picture view.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] There is no support for adding custom HTML buttons or controls.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The availability of picture-in-picture mode can be controlled using Permissions Policy.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] In this example, we have a `<video>` element in a web page, a `<button>` to toggle picture-in-picture, and an element to log information relevant for the example.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] The `<button>` element is `disabled` initially until we've determined browser support.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] We first check if the browser supports PiP with `document.pictureInPictureEnabled`, and if it's not supported, we log that information to the `<pre>` element.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] If it is available in the browser, we can enable the toggle to enter and exit PiP.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] For the controls, an event listener on the `<button>` element calls a `togglePictureInPicture()` function that we've defined.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture-api] In `togglePictureInPicture()`, an `if` statement checks the value of the `document`'s `pictureInPictureElement` attribute.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] For televisions, picture-in-picture requires two independent tuners or signal sources to supply the large and the small picture.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Two-tuner PiP TVs have a second tuner built in, but a single-tuner PiP TV requires an external signal source, which may be an external tuner, videocassette recorder, DVD player, or cable box.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Picture-in-picture is often used to watch one program while waiting for another to start or advertisements to finish.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Adding a picture to an existing picture was done long before affordable PiP was available on consumer products.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] The first PiP was seen on the televised coverage of the 1976 Summer Olympics where a Quantel digital framestore device was used to insert a close-up picture of the Olympic flame during the opening ceremony.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] In 1978 Sharp introduced its TV in TV "Mr.X" (CT-1804 X) in Japan; the export version began in 1979 as "Dualvision" (17D50).
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] In 1980, NEC introduced its "Popvision" television (CV-20T74P) in Japan with a rudimentary picture-aside-picture feature: a separate 6 in (15 cm) CRT and tuner complemented the set's main 20 in (51 cm) screen.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] An early consumer implementation of picture-in-picture was the Multivision set-top box; it was not a commercial success.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Later, PiP became available as a feature of advanced television receivers.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] The first widespread consumer implementation of picture-in-picture was produced by Philips in 1983 in their high-end television sets.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] A separate video or RF input was available on the back of the set and displayed in black and white on one of the four corners of the screen.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Televisions at the time were still in analog format, and earlier versions of the PiP implemented in analog were too costly.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] New digital technology allowed the second video signal to be digitized and saved in a digital memory chip, then replayed in a mini version.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] While the new technology was not good enough for color or full-screen viewing, it did provide a low-cost PiP feature.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] The Blu-ray Disc and HD DVD specifications included picture-in-picture, allowing viewers to see content such as the director's commentary on a film they are watching.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] All the Blu-ray Disc titles in 2006 and 2007 that had a PiP track used two separate HD encodings, with one of the HD encodings including a hard-coded PiP track.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Starting in 2008 Blu-ray Disc titles started being released that use one HD and one SD video track which can be combined with a Bonus View or BD-Live player.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] This method uses less disc space, allowing for PiP to be more easily added to a title.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Several studios released Bonus View PiP Blu-ray Disc titles in 2008 such as *Aliens vs.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Predator: Requiem*, *Resident Evil: Extinction*, *V for Vendetta*, and *War*.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] In 2011, after DirecTV released the HR34 Home Media Center HD DVR, picture-in-picture was introduced to all HD DVR models onwards; The feature has five options: Upper Left, Upper Right, Lower Right, Lower Left, and Side-by-Side.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Some streaming video websites may minimize a video stream similarly when browsing outside the playback page.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] Some web browsers (including Google Chrome, Firefox, and Safari) provide APIs or similar functions that allow a playing video to be opened in a pop-up overlay atop other applications.
[src:picture-in-picture/picture-in-picture] The mobile operating systems Android (starting with Android 7.0 for Android TV devices and Android 8.0 for other devices) and iOS (starting with iOS 14) similarly provide native APIs for picture-in-picture overlays.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] The read-only **`pictureInPictureElement`** property of the `Document` interface returns the `Element` that is currently being presented in picture-in-picture mode in this document, or `null` if picture-in-picture mode is not currently in use.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] Although this property is read-only, it will not throw if it is modified (even in strict mode); the setter is a no-operation and will be ignored.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] A reference to the `Element` object that's currently in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] Returns `null` if the document has no associated element in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] For example, there's no picture-in-picture element, or the element is from an iframe.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] This example presents a function, `exitPictureInPicture()`, which tests the value returned by `pictureInPictureElement`.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpictureelement] If the document is in picture-in-picture mode (`pictureInPictureElement` isn't `null`), `Document.exitPictureInPicture()` is run to exit picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpicturewindow] The **`PictureInPictureWindow`** interface represents an object able to programmatically obtain the **`width`** and **`height`** and **`resize event`** of the floating video window.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpicturewindow] An object with this interface is obtained using the `HTMLVideoElement.requestPictureInPicture()` promise return value.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpicturewindow] Determines the width of the floating video window.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpicturewindow] Determines the height of the floating video window.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpicturewindow] Sent to a `PictureInPictureWindow` when the floating video window is resized.
[src:picture-in-picture/pictureinpicturewindow] Given a `<button>` and a `<video>`, clicking the button will make the video enter the picture-in-picture mode; we then attach an event to print the floating video window dimensions to the console.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] The **`HTMLVideoElement`** method **`requestPictureInPicture()`** issues an asynchronous request to display the video in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] It's not guaranteed that the video will be put into picture-in-picture.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] If permission to enter that mode is granted, the returned `Promise` will resolve and the video will receive an `enterpictureinpicture` event to let it know that it's now in picture-in-picture.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] A `Promise` that will resolve to a `PictureInPictureWindow` object that can be used to listen when a user will resize that floating window.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] Thrown if the feature is not supported (for example, disabled by a user preference or by a platform limitation).
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] Thrown if the feature is blocked by a Permissions Policy.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] Thrown if the video element's `readState` is `HAVE_NOTHING`, or if the video element has no video track, or if the video element's `disablePictureInPicture` attribute is `true`.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] Thrown if `document.pictureInPictureElement` is `null` and the document does not have transient activation.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] The user has to interact with the page or a UI element for this feature to work.
[src:picture-in-picture/requestpictureinpicture] This example requests that the video enters Picture-in-Picture mode, and sets an event listener to handle the floating window resizing.
